1
00:00:01,802 --> 00:00:18,731
Namo dasa bhagavato harahato sama sambodasa Namo dasa bhagavato harahato sama sambodasa

2
00:00:19,504 --> 00:00:46,676
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa homage to the buddha the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one i've got my little microphone as usual so uh being spring or april anyway i thought we would uh have a go at joy

3
00:00:47,921 --> 00:01:16,156
the first thing i did was to look up all the synonyms we have so the pleasure enjoyment happiness gladness delight thrill exaltation elation bliss ecstasy rapture and absorption that's not bad is it and it's all good see it's not as though the buddha asked us to be miserable all the time even though he

4
00:01:16,593 --> 00:01:19,397
even though most of the teaching is about getting rid of suffering.

5
00:01:22,403 --> 00:01:27,614
You know, he was asked, how does he feel when he teaches and somebody doesn't accept the teaching?

6
00:01:28,015 --> 00:01:29,516
So he said he feels all right with it.

7
00:01:29,638 --> 00:01:30,840
It's calmer.

8
00:01:31,340 --> 00:01:36,710
But when somebody does accept his teaching, he feels happy, feels joyful.

9
00:01:40,099 --> 00:01:47,308
Now, it's an interesting thing that all my teachers never introduced us into the practice of joy.

10
00:01:48,009 --> 00:01:55,558
It's very strange, meta, meta all the time, compassion a little bit, but joy never.

11
00:01:56,218 --> 00:02:04,048
And it always, I don't know why, well, I'm thinking that why they did it because of the problem of indulgence.

12
00:02:05,750 --> 00:02:07,972
And I think that's what goes wrong, of course.

13
00:02:08,532 --> 00:02:17,883
All these beautiful mental states to which we are heir of corrupt as soon as we try to hold on to them or want more of them.

14
00:02:19,866 --> 00:02:29,056
So it's a case of recognizing that nothing is repeatable and that when it's gone, it's gone and there's no point in anchoring after it.

15
00:02:29,526 --> 00:02:39,177
So that, for instance, if you take a morsel of food which you delight in, you know, once you've swallowed it and you've got the aftertaste gone, that's it, let go.

16
00:02:39,217 --> 00:02:47,706
Now this fear, this fear of indulgence actually destroys joy.

17
00:02:47,747 --> 00:02:54,153
And I noticed it in the monastic life more than in lay people.

18
00:02:55,014 --> 00:02:56,597
So for instance,

19
00:02:56,812 --> 00:03:09,598
At the monastery, Kandamoda, there would be obviously occasions when people would come with special foods to celebrate a birthday, a marriage, and so on and so forth.

20
00:03:09,617 --> 00:03:15,969
And one of the things that is quite lovely is buffalo curd, miikiri.

21
00:03:16,709 --> 00:03:30,311
And it was handed out, you see, and you put loads of sugar with it, or kittel juice, a bit like maple juice, you know, and it's wonderful.

22
00:03:30,972 --> 00:03:42,430
And we're all eating it, you see, and there was a monk sat next to me who was the picture of the ascetic, you know, very gaunt, and his cheeks were like this, you know, and...

23
00:03:42,578 --> 00:03:43,519
And I knew him, you know.

24
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:52,933
And as we got round, while we were eating, he was glaring, as it were, at this curd, you know.

25
00:03:52,993 --> 00:04:02,870
And as we came to the finish, he sort of leant forward quite slowly, lifted it up slowly, and then basically shoveled it down his throat.

26
00:04:04,512 --> 00:04:09,479
And I've always presumed he was just so afraid of indulgence.

27
00:04:11,552 --> 00:04:17,771
So that's no good, is it?

28
00:04:19,154 --> 00:04:20,459
There was another case, too.

29
00:04:21,541 --> 00:04:25,713
There was my teacher, Sayadaw Ujanaka.

30
00:04:26,031 --> 00:04:47,500
uh about i would say around about 10 years ago he taught at a place called beatenberg which is uh near it's in interlaken which is right you know those beautiful lakes in uh switzerland and from it on a beautiful day you can see these three great mountains the eiger the monk and the jungfrau anyway

31
00:04:47,480 --> 00:05:10,247
uh during the retreat the weather was miserable rainy cloudy etc and one day it all opened up and it's a glorious sight the white peaks against this deep blue sky you know so everybody on the retreat went out onto the balcony and outside to have a look you see well he gave him hell didn't he he upset a lot of people he told them they were useless meditators

32
00:05:11,002 --> 00:05:35,103
were just indulging and he's wasting his time and all sorts so uh i don't think he was invited again and i remember whenever i would say something like uh you know isn't that a beautiful flower he would say ah yes but it fades you know it fades it dies so a bit of a killjoy really but his intention of course was to awaken me to the problem of indulgence

33
00:05:36,569 --> 00:05:40,302
And that seed of indulgence is always there, you know, right to the bitter end.

34
00:05:41,446 --> 00:05:46,764
Mara is always right there, just waiting for the moment to creep up on us.

35
00:05:48,415 --> 00:06:15,012
so uh it's a case of just recognizing these two things that uh if we if we begin to see what the what the consequences of indulgence are then we'll be we'll make ourselves afraid to enjoy something but actually if for instance you have a biscuit right and you finish a biscuit the last thing goes down flavor's gone and then you get this i think i'll have another one

36
00:06:15,752 --> 00:06:19,156
So as soon as that comes, you know, well, that's greed, right?

37
00:06:19,517 --> 00:06:23,202
So you have to sit there and wait for that to exhaust itself.

38
00:06:23,723 --> 00:06:31,874
Now, once you've done that, you've exhausted the karmic consequence of the greed that arose while you were eating that biscuit.

39
00:06:32,595 --> 00:06:34,117
I think it's as simple as that.

40
00:06:36,319 --> 00:06:39,903
I know somebody who got into the habit of eating biscuits just before they went to bed.

41
00:06:41,605 --> 00:06:43,528
And he was getting rather afraid of it.

42
00:06:43,949 --> 00:06:46,172
So instead, he turned to music.

43
00:06:46,452 --> 00:06:48,055
And now that's a skillful thing.

44
00:06:48,194 --> 00:06:57,750
If you find that, you know, an indulgence feels a little bit overwhelming, then put your attention on some other joyful thing that you like to do.

45
00:07:00,613 --> 00:07:01,435
So there we are.

46
00:07:01,456 --> 00:07:02,456
There's the fear.

47
00:07:02,798 --> 00:07:07,305
The fear of indulgence undermines, destroys enjoyment of joy.

48
00:07:07,324 --> 00:07:09,367
And to...

49
00:07:09,584 --> 00:07:14,702
to become indulgent with our joys, wanting more of this, more of the same.

50
00:07:14,723 --> 00:07:17,754
It's just the old suffering.

51
00:07:19,507 --> 00:07:28,535
So now the question is, why is it we remember mostly at the end of the day, the painful parts and hardly any of the joys, right?

52
00:07:28,555 --> 00:07:31,557
Well, I suppose the reason is because painful things hurt.

53
00:07:32,980 --> 00:07:36,322
But unfortunately, it does shadow out the joys of the day.

54
00:07:36,903 --> 00:07:40,987
So we have to make a special effort to remember the joys of the day, right?

55
00:07:41,007 --> 00:07:48,213
Instead of obsessing about our failures and our upsets, we can contemplate the successes and joys of the day.

56
00:07:49,072 --> 00:07:59,110
Now, the interesting thing is, the more you make yourself aware of the joys of the day, the more you bend that way and the more you see what is actually undermining your joy.

57
00:07:59,130 --> 00:08:02,656
And this, of course, creates even greater joy.

58
00:08:05,281 --> 00:08:12,295
So we try to rid ourselves of behaviours which undermine our joy and over time our joy grows.

59
00:08:16,038 --> 00:08:20,064
And of course, this is done with a certain affectionate awareness.

60
00:08:20,084 --> 00:08:26,735
And this is towards ourselves, you know, being kind to ourselves, gentle to ourselves and seeking what lifts the heart.

61
00:08:26,896 --> 00:08:31,043
Yeah, music, nature, friendship and so on.

62
00:08:33,672 --> 00:08:48,306
Now, this word mudita, which is one of the four Brahma-viharas, remember, so love, compassion, joy, and peacefulness, equanimity, are the four great mental states.

63
00:08:48,326 --> 00:08:52,254
These we can develop indefinitely.

64
00:08:52,572 --> 00:08:57,479
And it's often translated as appreciative joy, reciprocal joy.

65
00:08:58,461 --> 00:09:02,667
And what this does, of course, is it undermines envy and jealousy.

66
00:09:03,148 --> 00:09:14,445
And I define those two as saying that envy is wanting what the other person has and jealousy is wanting what the other person has and hating them for having it in the first place.

67
00:09:16,096 --> 00:09:28,701
Now, it's interesting in the East, you know, if you make a donation to a cause, if you make a donation to a, say, a monastery, all the names are posted up with exactly how much you gave.

68
00:09:28,842 --> 00:09:35,416
You know, so it starts off with, I don't know, maybe a thousand pounds and it goes all the way down to, you know, a couple of shillings.

69
00:09:36,197 --> 00:09:37,259
That's an old word, isn't it?

70
00:09:37,678 --> 00:10:05,037
so if you if you and it's done because in the east it's understood that people will rejoice in the good karma that you have gained by your offering now when it came to bill gates giving his millions away i wonder what our response was you know well he got all that money he should be able to give something away you know the one percenters

71
00:10:05,842 --> 00:10:10,089
Did we say, oh, good on Bill, you know, may he receive many blessings.

72
00:10:10,990 --> 00:10:12,371
So he's got enough blessings.

73
00:10:15,176 --> 00:10:21,465
So here we have that sort of reciprocal joy of actually being joyful in somebody else's successes and joys.

74
00:10:22,046 --> 00:10:28,475
And I think it comes as a revelation that we can actually be more joyful for others than for ourselves.

75
00:10:29,155 --> 00:10:35,445
And this is not strange, of course, to parents who rejoice in the successes of their offsprings.

76
00:10:35,981 --> 00:10:58,918
know i remember once uh i must have been about maybe 12 years old because my sister's 11 years younger than me and i got back from school and i sat opposite my mother and she held uh maria you see and encouraged her to walk towards me and of course when she did i mean it was joy you know it was wonderful to see this little this little toddler trying to make his way

77
00:11:00,485 --> 00:11:11,519
So this development of being joyful for other people in the joys of other people and the successes of other people is really heartlifting.

78
00:11:13,841 --> 00:11:16,524
And joy is also a restorative.

79
00:11:16,705 --> 00:11:18,407
Somebody's called it restorative joy.

80
00:11:18,427 --> 00:11:20,889
So there you are down in the dumps, right?

81
00:11:22,168 --> 00:11:25,375
And you think to yourself, well, how can I lift my heart?

82
00:11:25,755 --> 00:11:28,500
How can I bring joy into my heart?

83
00:11:28,881 --> 00:11:33,451
Whatever level, it doesn't always have to be amazing ecstatic joy.

84
00:11:33,510 --> 00:11:35,875
It's just feeling happy, generally happy.

85
00:11:36,717 --> 00:11:43,029
So that's when you meet up with a friend or you watch a good film and so on.

86
00:11:43,229 --> 00:11:48,453
In the monastic life, of course, the daily routine tends to be the same.

87
00:11:49,234 --> 00:11:56,640
I mean, even when there's a feast day, the only difference is you turn up for a better meal and then you go back and it's just the same.

88
00:11:57,341 --> 00:12:04,006
So it can be very, you know, it can move you towards a sense of apathy, a sense of laziness and all that.

89
00:12:04,868 --> 00:12:10,432
And it was then that I realized the amazing power of a long, mindful cup of tea.

90
00:12:12,014 --> 00:12:12,914
No doubt about it.

91
00:12:17,013 --> 00:12:38,548
So, I mean, if we just list all those things, you know, this is not an exhaustive list, but, you know, just the sensual joys that we get that lift the heart, relations of happiness, just the religious joys of, you know, feast days.

92
00:12:38,798 --> 00:12:44,163
Now the ethical joys are really what the Buddha points to, right?

93
00:12:44,183 --> 00:12:48,928
So as far as he's concerned, virtue goodness equals happiness.

94
00:12:49,929 --> 00:12:55,535
And in chapter 20 of the Dhammapada, which is a lot of the verses are devoted to being happy.

95
00:12:56,817 --> 00:12:57,677
This is what he says.

96
00:12:58,658 --> 00:13:07,168
Oh, how happily we live without hate among those with hate, among people who hate we live without hate.

97
00:13:08,211 --> 00:13:14,735
Oh, so how happily we live without misery among those in misery.

98
00:13:15,418 --> 00:13:18,610
Among people in misery, we live without misery.

99
00:13:19,298 --> 00:13:46,133
oh how happily we live without ambition among those with ambition among people with ambition we live without ambition now just a note on that ambition there's nothing wrong with us offering our talents for the benefit of the company um people etc etc but of course it becomes corrupt we start thinking about money and power

100
00:13:48,626 --> 00:13:53,322
So the whole idea really, if we want to develop joy is to bend that way.

101
00:13:55,158 --> 00:13:55,938
So here it is.

102
00:13:55,979 --> 00:13:57,181
So what have we talked about?

103
00:13:57,221 --> 00:13:59,443
We've talked about the enemies of joy.

104
00:14:00,284 --> 00:14:10,438
We realize how corruptive indulgence is, how it becomes an obsession, how it's, what they call it, feeding the dragon.

105
00:14:11,019 --> 00:14:17,168
And because of that, we can't allow ourselves to enjoy something.

106
00:14:17,727 --> 00:14:21,594
And then of course, there's the indulgence itself, which becomes a trap in itself.

107
00:14:21,634 --> 00:14:23,375
That's feeding the dragon.

108
00:14:24,875 --> 00:14:32,982
And the way we do it is by becoming more aware of our daily joys and just bending life towards that way, just as we do with metta.

109
00:14:34,144 --> 00:14:42,373
And then we have this reciprocal joy, you know, undermining envy and jealousy and really being happy for other people's happiness.

110
00:14:43,374 --> 00:14:48,298
And finally to use joy to lift the heart when we feel a bit down in the dumps.

111
00:14:48,619 --> 00:14:48,859
Yeah.

112
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:52,822
So here are some exercises.

113
00:14:55,164 --> 00:14:56,888
You have to make a resolution, you see.

114
00:14:56,967 --> 00:15:03,118
If at the end of today, you sit and you think now, you know, how happy was I today?

115
00:15:03,197 --> 00:15:04,620
And all you can remember is the miseries.

116
00:15:05,562 --> 00:15:13,695
Then you have to make a determination that tomorrow, you'll actually acknowledge when you're happy, any level of happiness, any level of joy.

117
00:15:13,794 --> 00:15:15,817
It could just be contentment, right?

118
00:15:15,837 --> 00:15:16,960
And just to acknowledge it.

119
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:20,885
And doing that, of course, you remember it by the end of the day.

120
00:15:22,368 --> 00:15:34,970
The other thing you might try to do is to contemplate every evening for about a week, maybe five, 10 minutes, and just go back in your life and just think of all the joys you've had.

121
00:15:35,270 --> 00:15:36,913
All the joys you've had.

122
00:15:37,434 --> 00:15:41,000
And by the end of the week, you'll have a big smile on your face.

123
00:15:42,735 --> 00:15:46,249
And the other thing is the practice of joy, which is like Metta.

124
00:15:46,429 --> 00:15:53,977
So you go through all the categories, but the blessings are, may you be joyful, may you be ever more joyful.

125
00:15:54,346 --> 00:15:58,352
Now those are the, shall we say, the ones that are regularly used.

126
00:15:58,913 --> 00:16:04,644
I like to add, may you attain the sublime peace of nibbana.

127
00:16:04,663 --> 00:16:09,673
Now the problem with nibbana is that there's no emotions in nibbana, right?

128
00:16:10,394 --> 00:16:12,979
So it's not that sort of happiness.

129
00:16:13,499 --> 00:16:15,523
In fact, that's what Sariputta said.

130
00:16:15,543 --> 00:16:19,731
He says it's the very absence of emotions which is the bliss of nibbana.

131
00:16:20,173 --> 00:16:28,910
That's a bit difficult for us, but at least we can, shall we say, make that intention because, you know, according to the Buddha, this is the highest of all happinesses.

132
00:16:30,092 --> 00:16:33,921
So, may you be joyful, may you be ever more joyful,

133
00:16:34,120 --> 00:16:36,884
May you attain the sublime peace of the abhorrent.

134
00:16:37,144 --> 00:16:38,647
So I think peace rather than bliss.

135
00:16:38,706 --> 00:16:40,149
I've sometimes used bliss.

136
00:16:41,291 --> 00:16:44,836
You know, peace gives you, I think, a slightly better feel for it.

137
00:16:48,942 --> 00:16:54,831
And as I say, at the end of this hour, that's what I'll be doing.

138
00:16:54,890 --> 00:16:58,677
I'll be doing joyful meditation instead of metta.

139
00:17:01,558 --> 00:17:02,400
Very good.

140
00:17:02,740 --> 00:17:15,265
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused confusion, and that by your development of joy, you will be joyful sooner rather than later.

